00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:35.000
So, you know, one thing that's pretty cool about

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:36.990
- have you heard of the AT protocol?

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:40.420
Some of you call it at proto for some reason - is

00:00:40.420 --> 00:00:44.030
that it does like social stuff, but it's not just

00:00:44.220 --> 00:00:45.000
social media.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:48.350
And in fact, science is itself a social process and an

00:00:48.350 --> 00:00:50.000
entirely democratic one.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:55.000
And so we should also use social internet for science.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:57.000
And we could disco with data.

00:00:57.000 --> 00:00:59.990
What is the problem that this is looking at?

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.010
Well, it turns out that a lot of what happens around

00:01:04.100 --> 00:01:07.850
science, apart from the science itself, sucks.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:11.990
Data in the science universe is pretty bad.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:14.990
There's a ton of really cool data.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:18.310
Lots of people are sharing it in the open in all kinds

00:01:18.310 --> 00:01:20.720
of ways, but like, it's all siloed

00:01:20.720 --> 00:01:21.000
.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:23.000
It's really hard to discover.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:25.990
A lot of the servers are terribly slow.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:27.000
The APIs don't work.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:30.250
The portals are designed by, I think, grad students

00:01:30.250 --> 00:01:32.000
, maybe not scientists.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:34.750
So, you know, some of those things are pretty bad

00:01:34.750 --> 00:01:34.990
.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:37.480
And one of the big classics is, of course, like

00:01:37.720 --> 00:01:41.000
all these scientists putting all their data on GitHub.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:44.740
Because we all know that nothing bad happens on proprietary social media

00:01:44.740 --> 00:01:46.000
platforms, right?

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:48.990
So anyway, we're trying to like, you know,

00:01:49.150 --> 00:01:53.780
Tom Nicholas from Frost wrote this like really cool blog post about

00:01:53.780 --> 00:01:54.000
it.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:57.910
And it's important to think about this because you never know

00:01:57.910 --> 00:02:00.000
when you're going to need it.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:02.590
So one of the things I've worked on before, I

00:02:02.590 --> 00:02:06.690
was a small part of the New York Times team that collected

00:02:06.690 --> 00:02:11.030
data for the, you've probably sadly seen this, the

00:02:11.030 --> 00:02:12.000
COVID tracker.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:16.390
And what we had to do for that to work was scrape

00:02:16.390 --> 00:02:18.990
data from like all over.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:21.910
And that actually that the team got a Pulitzer Prize for

00:02:22.150 --> 00:02:26.850
web scraping, which is quite interesting in and of itself.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:30.990
Like the level at which this data was bad is terrible.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:33.000
So like Italy, for instance, did a good job.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:35.000
They put all their numbers on GitHub.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:36.000
It was really easy.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:38.000
It was JSON, et cetera.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:42.570
In the US, most of the time data was per county

00:02:42.570 --> 00:02:43.000
.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:45.990
And those counties all had different systems.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:49.200
So you had to have different scrapers per county at the

00:02:49.200 --> 00:02:49.990
US level.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:52.950
One of my favorite ones was France, which I worked on

00:02:52.950 --> 00:02:56.050
a scraper for where like every day someone would get all

00:02:56.210 --> 00:03:00.480
the numbers from all of France, paste them on the J

00:03:00.480 --> 00:03:03.930
PEG with like a nice textured background and put the J

00:03:03.930 --> 00:03:06.780
PEG on the web such that scraping that involved a lot

00:03:06.940 --> 00:03:10.200
of processing to clean it up enough to OCR it to

00:03:10.200 --> 00:03:10.990
get the data out.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:14.310
And so this is the kind of situation where you do need

00:03:14.310 --> 00:03:14.990
stuff.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:18.600
And like more generally, even without COVID, you know,

00:03:18.600 --> 00:03:22.250
like if you imagine the impact of making research better, like

00:03:22.250 --> 00:03:25.760
every time we make it slightly better, scientists can science more

00:03:25.760 --> 00:03:26.000
.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:28.990
And so what does like good look like?

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:31.980
Well, so in that blog post I referenced earlier, like

00:03:32.150 --> 00:03:35.010
you can think of like a number of properties that would be

00:03:35.010 --> 00:03:37.400
pretty cool to have in, you know, sort of like

00:03:37.560 --> 00:03:41.290
the scientific data space in terms of discovery of data repositories

00:03:41.290 --> 00:03:43.000
, data sets, et cetera.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:45.290
Um, and you know, you want it unified, everyone

00:03:45.290 --> 00:03:45.990
can find it.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:47.000
Of course it's free.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:48.000
It works.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:49.000
It works on any scale.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:51.090
I'm not going to read through all of it, like

00:03:51.090 --> 00:03:54.000
, but like all of these properties are pretty interesting.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:57.650
And Volcker, um, has made a tool with the

00:03:57.650 --> 00:04:00.990
IPF foundation called Matadisco.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:03.990
And what Matadisco does is extremely simple.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:08.430
It tracks data that gets published to all kinds of different,

00:04:08.430 --> 00:04:10.990
um, data sets and data sources.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:13.150
Currently it's limited to just a few because it's still

00:04:13.150 --> 00:04:13.990
like ramping up.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:16.990
But the idea is to put all the metadata around all,

00:04:17.150 --> 00:04:20.990
everything that happens, everything that's published, um, directly

00:04:21.210 --> 00:04:23.520
on AT Proto, such that then you can write apps

00:04:23.550 --> 00:04:27.570
that just listen to, uh, whatever jet stream, whatever

00:04:27.610 --> 00:04:29.330
's, whatever's convenient in terms of fire hoses for

00:04:29.330 --> 00:04:30.000
you.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:33.220
And then react to that and do things with that data,

00:04:33.220 --> 00:04:36.450
pull it down, et cetera, knowing of course that,

00:04:36.450 --> 00:04:39.000
um, all of this is nicely verified.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:41.710
And so if you, if you think of the list of

00:04:42.150 --> 00:04:45.990
properties that I, I, I produced earlier, well,

00:04:45.990 --> 00:04:48.000
it hits quite a number of them, right?

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:50.000
You have something that's inherently social.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:51.000
You can subscribe to it.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:53.490
You have a right to exit because it's all on the

00:04:53.660 --> 00:04:53.990
PDS.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:55.000
That's part of the protocol.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:57.000
And, you know, sustainably fundable.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:04:59.500
Well, it's not very expensive, um, but like

00:04:59.620 --> 00:05:02.000
we could, we could figure it out.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:03.520
Um, and, and there's a few properties that it

00:05:03.520 --> 00:05:06.450
doesn't completely hit, but in general, like simply by

00:05:06.540 --> 00:05:10.380
pushing all this metadata about data sets to the, to the

00:05:10.380 --> 00:05:13.980
protocol is getting a lot of these things working already.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:16.600
And so, um, I made, you know, a

00:05:16.600 --> 00:05:19.590
, a, a very simple, uh, demo of this

00:05:19.590 --> 00:05:20.000
.

